 \caption{Degree distribution of the simulated Erdős--Rényi network ($N=1000$, $\langle k\rangle \approx10$).}
 \label{fig:degree}
 \end{figure}
\subsection{Epidemic Model}
We adopted a network--based SIR process where a susceptible node $S$ acquires infection through contact with an infectious neighbor $I$ at rate $\beta$, and infectious nodes recover at rate $\gamma$.  The basic reproduction number on a configuration network is $R_{0}=\beta q/\gamma$.
\subsection{Parameterisation and Scenarios}
Two parameter sets were explored (Table~\ref{tab:params}).  Recovery was fixed at $\gamma=1/7\;\text{d}^{-1}$, reflecting a 7--day infectious period.  Scenario~A set $\beta$ such that $R_{0}\approx2.5$, typical of seasonal influenza, whereas Scenario~B used a four--fold larger $\beta$ to obtain $R_{0}\approx10$, mimicking highly transmissible pathogens.
