\subsection{Initial Condition and Simulation}
One percent of nodes were randomly seeded infectious; the remainder were susceptible.  Simulations employed the \textit{fastGEMF} Gillespie engine with stopping time $160$~days and single realisation per scenario (sufficient because variance is low in $N=10^{3}$ ER networks with large $R_{0}$).  State counts were saved every $\Delta t=0.1$~days.
\section{Analytical Expectations}
The canonical threshold theorem\cite{Anderson1991} states that infections decline once $S(t)<S_{c}=\gamma N/\beta=N/R_{0}$.  Defining $x(t)=S(t)/N$, $y(t)=I(t)/N$, the deterministic equations satisfy $dy/dt=\gamma y (R_{0} x-1)$.  Hence, $y$ peaks when $x=1/R_{0}$ and thereafter decays exponentially with rate $\gamma(1-R_{0}x)$.  If $R_{0}$ is modest, $x$ needs to drop only moderately below one for $dy/dt<0$, leaving many susceptibles uninfected.  Conversely, if $R_{0}\gg1$, $x$ must fall to near zero, implying near--total susceptible depletion.  These contrasting regimes motivate the two scenarios.
